	(text_box "WARNING - 3.3 V LOGIC. DO NOT CONNECT A 5 V DEBUG PROBE.\n\nThe Arduino Due (Atmel SAM3X8E) runs at 3.3 V, unlike most other Arduino boards.\nFrom the Arduino Due datasheet (A000062):\n\n    'Unlike most traditional Arduino boards, the Arduino Due board runs at 3.3 V.\n     Keep in mind the maximum voltage that the I/O pins can tolerate is 3.3 V.\n     Applying voltages higher than 3.3 V to any I/O pin could damage the board.'\n\nUse a 3.3 V probe, or one that sets its levels from VTref. Header pin 10 (+3V3) is the\nboard's 3.3 V rail and is what feeds the probe's VTref level reference."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 25.4 20.32 0)
		(size 165.1 33.02)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 214 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001")
	)
	(text_box "TWO WAYS TO GET FIRMWARE ONTO THIS BOARD - THIS SHEET DRAWS ONLY THE SECOND\n\n1. Programming USB port + bossac. No probe, no wiring, just the USB cable. SAM-BA lives in\n   the SAM3X ROM, and a 1200-baud touch on that port makes the ATmega16U2 assert ERASE +\n   RESET to drop the chip into it. This is what the repo's bossac Dagger module does today.\n\n2. SWD debug probe on the header below - what this drawing is about. Required for probe-rs\n   flashing, and the only route to breakpoints, memory inspection and GDB. A USB-to-serial\n   port cannot halt a core.\n\nBoth write the application to flash at 0x00080000, and neither locks you out of the other."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 25.4 57.15 0)
		(size 165.1 24.13)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 224 240 255 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000008")
	)
	(text_box "JTAG / SWD HEADER PIN NUMBERING - READ BEFORE WIRING\n\nThe Due's on-board 10-pin header carries the standard ARM Cortex Debug signal set,\nbut Arduino numbers the connector from the OPPOSITE END to the ARM standard:\n\n            Arduino pin N  ==  ARM Cortex Debug pin (11 - N)\n\n     Arduino | Signal | ARM Cortex Debug pin\n     --------+--------+----------------------\n        1    | RESET  |  10   nRESET\n        2    | GND    |   9   GNDDetect\n        3    | TDI    |   8   TDI\n        4    | N/C    |   7   KEY\n        5    | TDO    |   6   SWO / TDO\n        6    | GND    |   5   GND\n        7    | TCK    |   4   SWCLK / TCK\n        8    | GND    |   3   GND\n        9    | TMS    |   2   SWDIO / TMS\n       10    | +3V3   |   1   VTref\n\nSource: Arduino Due datasheet A000062, sections 6.2.6 and 6.5.1."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 203.2 20.32 0)
		(size 190.5 48.26)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 249 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000002")
	)
	(text_box "Required for\nprobe-rs SWD:\n\n  SWDIO\n  SWCLK\n  GND\n  VTref\n\nRecommended:\n\n  nRESET\n\nNot needed for\nSWD (JTAG only):\n\n  TDI\n  SWO / TDO"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 132.08 88.9 0)
		(size 40.64 45.72)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 224 240 255 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000003")
	)
	(text_box "WHY AN EXTERNAL LED, AND NOT THE ON-BOARD ONE\n\nThis LED is wired by you. The on-board D13 'L' LED is deliberately\nNOT used and is not driven by this firmware.\n\nAn on-board LED blinking is weak evidence: bootloader activity, or a\nwatchdog reset loop, can make the board blink on its own. Issue #3\ncalls out that exact failure mode - if the watchdog is not disabled,\nthe board resets every few seconds and 'the blink looks like a boot\nloop'. Those two cases are indistinguishable by eye on D13.\n\nPB26 / D22 has no on-board LED, no boot-time role, and no peripheral\nalternate function in the Arduino variant table. If it blinks at a\nsteady 1 Hz, the firmware is running and toggling a pin.\n\nActive high: driving PB26 high lights the LED.\n1 Hz = 500 ms high / 500 ms low."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 119.38 146.05 0)
		(size 106.68 40.64)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000004")
	)
	(text_box "WHERE TO WIRE IT - MIND THE +5V PIN NEXT DOOR\n\nUse the D22-D53 header, even-numbered (LHS) row. Counting along that row:\n\n     position  1  =  +5V     <-- DANGER: directly beside D22\n     position  2  =  D22     <-- LED anode side, through R1\n     position  3  =  D24\n        ...\n     position 18  =  GND     <-- LED cathode side\n\nD22 is the SECOND pin in that row, and the pin immediately next to it is\n+5V. Miscounting by one position feeds 5 V into a board whose I/O pins\ntolerate 3.3 V. Count twice, and confirm GND with a continuity check,\nbefore applying power.\n\nSource: Arduino Due datasheet A000062, section 6.2.4."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 232.41 146.05 0)
		(size 161.29 44.45)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 214 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000006")
	)
	(text_box "R1 = 1 k, giving roughly 1 mA through a red LED - dim but plainly visible\nindoors, and far inside spec.\n\nDo NOT reach for the reflexive 220 ohm. PB26 falls in the SAM3X datasheet's\nGroup 2 (PB[25-31]), whose source limit is IOH = -3 mA at VOH = VDDIO - 0.4 V,\nnot the -15 mA that Group 1 pins allow. At 220 ohm the LED would draw roughly\n4 mA, outside that spec. 470 ohm (about 2 mA) is the practical floor if you\nwant it brighter.\n\nSource: SAM3X / SAM3A datasheet, table 45-2 with notes 2 and 3."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 119.38 189.23 0)
		(size 106.68 25.4)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 249 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "10000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000007")
	)
	(text_box "BEFORE YOU WIRE ANYTHING - CONFIRM PIN 1\n\nA keyed 2x5 1.27 mm ribbon cable between a standard ARM Cortex Debug probe and this header mates correctly. The connectors are physically compatible, and the reversed\nnumbering documented above is a labelling convention, not a wiring difference - SEGGER lists the Arduino Due as a standard Cortex-M 10-pin target.\n\nIf you instead hand-wire flying leads, the two numbering conventions are exact opposites, and following the wrong one connects +3V3 to nRESET and vice versa. Identify pin 1 on\nthe physical board (silkscreen dot / square pad) and confirm it with a continuity check against a known GND pin before applying power.\n\nFlashing over SWD overwrites flash, but there is NO bootloader to lose - SAM-BA is burned into the SAM3X ROM at the factory and uses no flash space, so it cannot be erased. To go back to\nbossac, open the programming port at 1200 baud (the ATmega16U2 then asserts ERASE + RESET, dropping the chip into ROM SAM-BA) or press ERASE. probe-rs and bossac coexist; neither locks you out of the other."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 25.4 215.9 0)
		(size 368.3 30.48)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
